# AI-Native Team Scanner — Working Agreement with AI Tools
# This file defines how AI assistants collaborate on this project.
# It is the team's shared AI configuration, committed to version control
# so all contributors (human and AI) work from the same standards.

## Project Identity

This is the AI-Native Team Scanner (codenamed "Aints") — a GitHub repository
scanning tool that identifies teams which have genuinely integrated AI into
their development practices. It is built with Python and hosted at
https://github.com/robpurdie/ai-native-team-scanner.

The scanner uses a two-dimensional maturity model (AI Adoption + Engineering
Practices) scored at three levels: L0 (Not Yet), L1 (Integrating), L2 (AI-Native).
The overall level is always the lower of the two dimensions.

## Philosophy

- Done means working software, not design artifacts or documentation
- AI adoption and engineering discipline are inseparable — the lower-of-two rule
  encodes this as a core design principle
- Genuine AI integration must be distinguished from superficial adoption
- Never lower coverage thresholds to make tests pass — write proper tests instead

## Python Standards

- Python 3.9.6 compatibility required — use Optional/Union from typing, not | syntax
- Black for formatting (line length 100, configured in pyproject.toml)
- isort for import sorting
- flake8 for linting (max-line-length = 100, configured in .flake8)
- mypy for type checking
- All functions must have type annotations
- All classes and public functions must have docstrings

## Test-Driven Development

- Write tests BEFORE implementation (TDD)
- Acceptance tests written first as executable specifications
- Selective unit tests for deterministic scoring logic
- Never lower the coverage threshold (currently 80% minimum, typically 85%+)
- Test files live in tests/ and follow test_<module>.py naming

## Pre-Commit Workflow (always run before committing)

1. black src/ tests/
2. isort src/ tests/
3. flake8 src/ tests/
4. mypy src/
5. pytest --cov=src --cov-report=term-missing --cov-fail-under=80

Never commit without all checks passing locally.

## Branching Discipline

- main = stable releases only
- dev = active development, all new work happens here
- Never commit directly to main while external testers have access

## Architecture Principles

- scanner/models.py — data models only, no logic
- scanner/detectors.py — signal detection, no scoring
- scanner/scoring.py — threshold-based maturity scoring
- scanner/gap_analysis.py — gap calculations, no reporting
- scanner/reporter.py — markdown report generation, no scoring logic
- scanner/cli.py — CLI interface only, thin orchestration layer
- Keep modules single-responsibility and independently testable

## Documentation Standards

- No organisation-specific names in public GitHub documentation
- No references to named colleagues in committed files
- METHODOLOGY.md must be precise and defensible — high verifier audience
- Update PROJECT_CONTEXT.md at the end of each significant session
- Update CHANGELOG.md when releasing to main

## Output Quality Standards

- Report language must be meaningful to non-technical executives
- Gap analysis must give concrete counts, not just percentages
- Strategic roadmap must suppress guidance for thresholds already met
- The goal is always AI-Native (L2) — every limiting dimension statement
  should connect back to that north star
- "Test file ratio" not "test coverage" — these are different measurements

## What This Project Is Building Toward

The scanner is a reference implementation with Cisco as the pilot organisation.
The longer-term vision is a general-purpose tool for any organisation measuring
AI-native team capability. Phase 1 (composite scoring, gap analysis, reporting)
is complete. Phase 2 (batch scanning, comparative analysis) is next.
